knowledge_graph.title: F1
knowledge_graph.description: In the 1990s, Sonny Hayes was Formula 1's most promising driver until an accident on the track nearly ended his career. Thirty years later, the owner of a struggling Formula 1 team convinces Sonny to return to racing and become the best in the world. Driving alongside the team's hotshot rookie, Sonny soon learns that the road to redemption is not something you can travel alone.… MORE

related_questions.question: Should I watch F1 in IMAX or Dolby?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: Pros: Larger screen, powerful sound system, expanded aspect ratio (revealing more of the image), often steeper seating for better views.
Cons: IMAX seats can be similar to regular cinema seats.
Why it's good for F1: The larger screen and powerful sound can make the racing sequences feel incredibly immersive and exciting.
Pros: Enhanced visual depth and clarity, potentially more comfortable seating (depending on the theater), Dolby Atmos sound.
Cons: Screen size may be smaller than IMAX.
Why it's good for F1: The visual and audio quality can create a vibrant and realistic racing experience.
Pros: Moving seats, wind effects, vibrations, and other environmental effects that simulate the feeling of being in a racing car.
Cons: May not be suitable for those sensitive to motion or those who prefer a more traditional movie experience.
Why it's good for F1: The immersive effects can be very exciting and make you feel like you're actually on the track.

related_questions.question: What is the 75% rule in F1?
related_questions.snippet: If more than 75% of the scheduled race distance is completed, full points will be awarded. However, these rules do not apply and full points will be awarded when a race is suspended and then resumed, even if the whole race distance cannot be completed in the 3 hour race window.
related_questions.title: Formula One regulations - Wikipedia

related_questions.question: Why is number 17 banned in F1?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: The Incident: In the 2014 Japanese Grand Prix, Jules Bianchi suffered a severe head injury during a collision with a recovery vehicle.
The Aftermath: Bianchi fought for his life for nine months before succumbing to his injuries in 2015.
The Tribute: In response to this tragedy, the FIA retired number 17 as a permanent tribute to Bianchi's memory.
Permanent Retirement: This means that no Formula 1 driver will ever be allowed to use the number 17 again.
